                  </hi>. I paid the prisoner on the 20th of April 19<hi rend="italic">s</hi>. 5 3/4 <hi rend="italic">d</hi>., for his master.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18440506-name-724" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18440506-name-724" type="gender" value="female"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18440506-name-724" type="surname" value="PEARSON"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18440506-name-724" type="given" value="ELIZABETH"></interp>ELIZABETH PEARSON</persName>
                  </hi>. I paid the prisoner 7<hi rend="italic">s</hi>. for his master, on the 22nd of April.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">Prisoner.</hi> I was in his employ from about the 27th of July; it was his duty to settle my accounts every night, which he never did, from the first day I entered till I left him. He was in the habit of going and getting intoxicated, and staying out till two or three o'clock in the morning. He can't produce any cash-book, to show the accounts settled.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18440506-name-725" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18440506-name-725" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18440506-name-725" type="surname" value="POWRIE"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18440506-name-725" type="given" value="JOHN WHITE"></interp>JOHN WHITE POWRIE</persName>
                  </hi>. Here is my cash-book, provided for me by the prisoner—his accounts should have been settled every night, but owing to the irregularity of his coming in, I could not.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">JURY</hi>. <hi rend="italic">Q.</hi> Did he carry out bread for you? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> Yes—I sent bills out every week—I am so much engaged at home, I cannot go to my customers, to ascertain what mistakes existed—the prisoner took advantage of that, and I did not know how the accounts stood—he took so much time to serve his customers, and did not return till half-past ten o'clock at night—I was not</p>
               <xptr type="pageFacsimile" doc="184405060101"></xptr>
               <p>able to book his bread, and it remained till the end of the week, When we set<lb></lb>tled as well as we could—these amounts have never been paid to me—these sums are not entered—part of this book is in my writing, and part is the pri<lb></lb>soner's—he received Mrs. Pearson's on the 22nd of April, and absconded on that day—I received 18<hi rend="italic">s</hi>. 6<hi rend="italic">d</hi>. of him on the 21st, but that was not part of Mrs. Pedley's money—he told me there had been no bills paid him that week—I received no money of him on the 22nd, I distinctly swear.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">Prisoner.</hi> I paid him that day before I left.</p>
